c|first=|date=1910|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMares - Filomena (1894-1960)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:JJXX-H3J|title=New York Passenger Arrival Lists (Ellis Island), 1892-1924|last=Mares|first=|date=1910|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFilomena was the younger sister of Marie.\n|\n|-\n|11 February 1911\n[[SS George Washington]]\n\n[[Bremen]][[File:George Washington Dampfer.jpg|center|thumb|195x195px]]<br />\n|20 February 1911\n[[Ellis Island|New York]]\n|Skala - Marie (1891-1925)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:JJV5-PMX|title=New York Passenger Arrival Lists (Ellis Island), 1892-1924|last=Skala|first=|date=1911|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n|13 December 1913\n[[SS George Washington]]\n\n[[Bremen]][[File:George Washington Dampfer.jpg|center|thumb|195x195px]]<br />\n|22 December 1913\n\n[[Ellis Island|New York]]\n|Behensky - Josef (1898-1974)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:JNTV-R5Q|title=New York Passenger Arrival Lists (Ellis Island), 1892-1924|last=Behensky|first=|date=1913|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nSkala - Anna (1889-1946)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:JNTV-Y2K|title=New York Passenger Arrival Lists (Ellis Island), 1892-1924|last=Skala|first=|date=1913|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nJosef was the younger brother of Vaclav. Anna was the older sister of Marie.\n|\n|-\n|7 December 1920\n[[SS La Touraine]]\n\n[[Le Havre]][[File:SS La Touraine.jpg|center|thumb]]<br />\n|17 December 1920\n[[Ellis Island|New York]]\n|Popule - Marie (1904-1992)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:J6HD-Y62|title=New York Passenger Arrival Lists (Ellis Island), 1892-1924|last=Popule|first=|date=1920|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMarie was the niece of Marie Populova.\n|\n|-\n|4 May 1947\n[[RMS Queen Elizabeth]]\n\n[[Southampton]][[File:RMS Queen Elizabeth Southampton.jpg|center|thumb|At port in Southampton]]<br />\n|9 May 1947\n[[New York City|New York]]\n|Moutvic - Barbora (1893-)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:24PN-FMB|title=New York, New York Passenger and Crew Lists, 1909, 1925-1957|last=Moutvic|first=|date=1947|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nShe had a family in [[Prague]] and was probably only visiting her brother Karel.\n|\n|-\n|\n|before 1952\n|Mares - Frantisek (1920-2001)\n\nFrantisek was the nephew of Marie and Filomena Maresova.\n|\n|}\n\n== Population ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Population\n|-\n|1880\n|344<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.portafontium.eu/iipimage/34426168|title=Census 1880 Nehodiv (Nehodiw, Nehodivo), Nr. 47 {{!}} Porta fontium|website=www.portafontium.eu|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n|-\n|1890\n|293<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.portafontium.eu/iipimage/34426169/soap-kt_01159_census-sum-1890-nehodiv_0030?x=-40&y=268&w=541&h=239|title=Census 1890 Nehodiv (Nehodiw, Nehodivo) - souhrn / Sammelbogen {{!}} Porta fontium|website=www.portafontium.eu|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|1900\n|306<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.portafontium.eu/iipimage/34426219/soap-kt_01159_census-sum-1900-nehodiv_0160?x=260&y=69&w=680&h=301|title=Census 1900 Nehodiv (Nehodiw, Nehodivo) - souhrn / Sammelbogen {{!}} Porta fontium|website=www.portafontium.eu|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|1910\n|291<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.portafontium.eu/iipimage/34426270/soap-kt_01159_census-sum-1910-nehodiv_0020?x=229&y=-2&w=813&h=360|title=Census 1910 Nehodiv (Nehodiw, Nehodivo) - souhrn / Sammelbogen {{!}} Porta fontium|website=www.portafontium.eu|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|1921\n|262<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.portafontium.eu/iipimage/34426372?x=-57&y=437&w=1092&h=581|title=Census 1921 Nehodiv (Nehodiw, Nehodivo), Nr. 52 {{!}} Porta fontium|website=www.portafontium.eu|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n|-\n|28&nbsp;August 2006\n|79\n|}\n\n== Facts ==\nThere is a chapel with a computer-controlled bell in the center of the village. There is also a limestone quarry from which white limestone is extracted. The village is towered by St\u00edrka Hill, which dominates the general area with its height of 702 m above sea level. Southwest of the village is a natural monument Dolejsi drahy .\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Nehodiv, zat\u00e1\u010dka.jpg|Houses\nFile:Nehodiv6.jpg|House\nFile:Nehodiv5.jpg|Village square with tree\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080618131004/http://www.czso.cz/lexikon/mos_vdb.nsf/okresy/CZ0322/ Czech Statistical Office: Municipalities of Klatovy District]\n\n{{commons category|Nehodiv}}\n{{Klatovy District}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Klatovy District]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Nehodiv\n| settlement_type                 = Municipality\n| image_skyline                   = Nehodiv, n\u00e1ves III.jpg\n| image_caption                   = View towards Nehodiv\n| image_shield                    = Nehodiv znak.jpg\n| image_flag                      = Nehodiv vlajka.jpg\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{CZE}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Regions of the Czech Republic|Region]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Plze\u0148 Region|Plze\u0148]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[Districts of the Czech Republic|District]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Klatovy District|Klatovy]]\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|49|24|38|N|13|33|13|E|region:CZ|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map                     = Czech Republic\n| area_total_km2                  = 3.94\n| population_total                = 72\n| population_as_of                = 1.1.2015\n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| elevation_m                     = 607\n| postal_code_type                = Postal&nbsp;code\n| postal_code                     = 341&nbsp;01\n| official_name                   = \n| website                         = https://www.nehodiv.cz/\n}}\n\n'''Nehodiv''' is a village and municipality (''[[obec]]'') in [[Klatovy District]] in the [[Plze\u0148 Region]] of the Czech Republic.\n\nThe municipality covers an area of {{convert|3.94|km2|sqmi}}, and has a population of 79 (as at 28&nbsp;August 2006).\n\nNehodiv lies approximately {{convert|20|km|mi|0}} east of [[Klatovy]], {{convert|40|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} south of [[Plze\u0148]], and {{convert|98|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} south-west of [[Prague]].\n\nFrom the mid 1800's to early 1900's, around 90 of its inhabitants have been documented as immigrating to [[United States|America]].\n\nHistoric parish: [[Mysl\u00edv]]\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Mysl\u00edv, kostel Nanebevzet\u00ed Panny Marie.jpg|left|thumb|Mysl\u00edv's church|95x95px]]\nThe first written mention of the village dates back to 1558. Its name is allegedly based on [[scorpion]]s that once lived there, now represented in its flag. Its Catholic parish seat has traditionally been [[Mysl\u00edv]]. Surnames of the village reaching back to the 17th century include Liska, Popule, Cihla, Ciz, and Ticha.\n\n== Genealogy and Immigration to America ==\nSo far, about 88 people born in Nehodiv have been identified as immigrating to America, sorted and profiled on [[FamilySearch]], a high ratio given a population averaging around 300. The earliest [[Immigration|immigrant]] from the village was probably Josefa Zelena (1835-1892) with her husband from Mysliv, Jan Rada, and children who settled in [[Baltimore]] in 1869. She was followed by Josef Kle\u010dka (1852-1926) who arrived in 1870. There he married Marie Hrani\u010dkov\u00e1 (1851-1913) from [[Kv\u00e1\u0161\u0148ovice]]. Josef returned multiple times to visit his mother and siblings, perhaps encouraging other villagers to follow him.\n\nOther early immigrants include V\u00e1clav Kon\u010dal (1843-1925) who brought his wife Marie V\u00ed\u0161kov\u00e1 (1844-1906) to [[Saint Paul, Minnesota]] around the same year. Never having biological children, the couple adopted V\u00e1clav's brother son V\u00e1clav and Marie's sister's daughter Josefa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:M93F-QVF|title=United States Census, 1900|last=Konchal|first=|date=|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nA significant number of the immigrants share a [[Genetic testing|DNA]] and blood relation via children of the couple Krystof Sramek (1700-1767) and Katerina Hithova (1705-1760) from Klikarov, Vojovice, and [[Lou\u017en\u00e1|Louzna]] in the 18th century.\n\n* Katerina Sramkova (1727-1798) is the ancestor of the Kotesovec's and the Popule's.\n*Dorota Sramkova (1730-1796) is the ancestor of the Protova's, Blazek's, and Vojtech Zeleny (specifically).\n*Ondrej Sramek (1743-) is the great grandfather of the Poustkova sisters. Josefa Poustkova is the ancestor of the Stepan's (DNA) and Melichar's (DNA). Marie Poustkova is the ancestor of the Klecka's. Ludmila Poustkova is the ancestor of the Mares', Behensky's and Hlavac's.\n* Simon Sramek (c. 1745-1813) is the ancestor of Frantisek Koncal's wife Frantiska Sramkova (from [[Mysl\u00edv|Mysliv]]) as well as Stipek DNA matches from other villages.\n\nSome other immigrants also share relation through the couple Jan Franek and Dorota Sourova.\n\nThe immigrants are listed as follows (women are paired with their maiden names):\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Embarkation\n!Arrival\n!Immigrants\n!Photos\n|-\n|[[SS Baltimore]]\n[[Bremen]][[File:SS_Baltimore_1868.jpg|center|thumb]]\n|14 August 1869\n[[Baltimore]]\n|[https://www.familysearch.org/tree/person/details/L146-CL9 Zeleny - Josefa (1835-1892)] [with her husband from [[Mysl\u00edv|Mysliv]], Jan Rada, and children]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QK6L-HDPJ|title=Maryland, Baltimore Passenger Lists, 1820-1948|last=Zeleny|first=|date=1869|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n|Str. Baltimore\n[[Bremen]]\n|7 May 1870\n[[Baltimore]]\n|[https://www.familysearch.org/tree/person/details/L171-6G6 Klecka - Josef (1852-1926)]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QK6L-HK6J|title=Maryland, Baltimore Passenger Lists, 1820-1948|last=Klecka|first=|date=1870|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Az0_DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT119&lpg=PT119&dq=August+Klecka+roosevelt&source=bl&ots=EWRb547Nr5&sig=ACfU3U24JTKwfg4n1ZZFiDMiNOANE98-og&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiRo87c4q_nAhUUqp4KHUF2C4YQ6AEwAXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=August%20Klecka%20roosevelt&f=false|title=Beyond the Sea of Beer: History of Immigration of Bohemians and Czechs to the New World and Their Contributions|last=Jr|first=Miloslav Rechcigl|date=2017-11-09|publisher=AuthorHouse|isbn=978-1-5462-0237-0|language=en}}</ref>\n\nHis son [[August Klecka]] was the first [[Czech Americans|Czech-American]] elected to the [[Baltimore City Council]]. Another son James became Chief Magistrate of the People's Court of [[Baltimore]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/372925155/?terms=joseph+klecka+died+magistrate+people%27s+court|title=19 Jan 1926, 18 - The Baltimore Sun at Newspapers.com|website=Newspapers.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1991-02-26-1991057107-story.html|title=The people's court|last=SANDLER|first=GILBERT|website=baltimoresun.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n|[[File:Joseph Emil Kle\u010dka (1852-1926).png|center|thumb|170x170px|Joseph Emil Kle\u010dka Sr. (1852-1926)]]\n|-\n|\n|c. 1870\n|Koncal - Vaclav (1843-1925) [early census]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:MZ92-M74|title=United States Census, 1880|last=Koncal|first=|date=1880|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\nVisek - Marie (1844-1906) [wife of Vaclav Koncal]\n|\n|-\n|\n|c. 1876\n|[https://www.familysearch.org/tree/person/details/L18H-S7C Hulec - Barbora (1864-1953]) [also lived in Louzna]\n|\n|-\n|\n|c. 1879\n|Zeleny - Jan (1864-1899)\n\nJan was the nephew of Josefa.\n|\n|-\n|SS Hermann\n[[Bremen]][[File:SS_Hermann.jpg|alt=|center|thumb|SS Hermann]]\n|7 May 1880\n[[Baltimore]]\n|Koncal - Petr (1845-1909) [with his wife from [[Mysl\u00edv]], Frantiska Protivova, and 4 children],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QK6L-ZTJB|title=Maryland, Baltimore Passenger Lists, 1820-1948|last=Koncal|first=|date=1880|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Marie (1873-), Frantisek (1874-1903), Frantiska (1877-1915), Anna (1979-)\n\nPetr had a history of domestic violence. He hung himself in 1909 over the suicide of Josefa Ursova a few weeks prior (the [[Lou\u017en\u00e1|Louzna]]-born adoptive daughter of his brother Vaclav). He possibly told her about mental problems in her biological family.\n|\n|-\n|\n|c. 1880\n|[https://www.familysearch.org/tree/person/details/G7SZ-155 Hulec - Antonie (1853-1929)] [with her husband and son from [[Nekvasovy]]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:MK8K-3WB|title=United States Census, 1910|last=Hulec|first=|date=1910|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n|\n|c. 1881\n|Zeleny -  Vojtech (1843-1921), Marie (1868-), Josefa (1871-1946), Anezka (1876-1974), Barbora (1878-1973)\nProtiva - Josefa (1845-1921) [wife of Vojtech Zeleny]\n|\n|-\n|SS Salier\n[[Bremen]]\n|16 May 1882\n[[New York City|New York]]\n|[https://www.familysearch.org/tree/person/details/L133-F73 Havlik - Josef (1853-1940),]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QVS2-NQHX|title=New York Passenger Lists, 1820-1891|last=Havlik|first=|date=1882|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  [https://www.familysearch.org/tree/person/details/MWGV-FX8 Marie (1882-1960)]\n\n[https://www.familysearch.org/tree/person/details/L133-GC1 Hulec - Ruzena (1862-1914)] [wife of Josef Havlik]\n\nRuzena was the older sister of Barbora.\n|\n|-\n|\n|c. 1882\n[[Baltimore]]\n|Melichar - Karolina (1863-1948)\n\nShe married Josef Komin (from Zahori) in Baltimore.\n|\n|-\n|SS Hohenstaufen\n[[Bremen]]\n|27 April 1883\n[[Baltimore]]\n|Budka - Josef (1867-) [might have returned to Bohemia later]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QK6L-6W2Y|title=Maryland, Baltimore Passenger Lists, 1820-1948|last=Budka|first=|date=1883|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nKoncal - Frantisek (1848-1918) [with his wife from Mysliv, Frantiska Sramkova, and 5 children also from Mysliv]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QK6L-6W2X|title=Maryland, Baltimore Passenger Lists, 1820-1948|last=Koncal|first=|date=1883|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n<br />\n|\n|-\n|[[SS Weser (1867)|SS Weser]]\n[[Bremen]][[File:SS_Weser_1867.jpg|center|thumb|122x122px]]\n|6 July 1883\n[[Baltimore]]\n|Melichar - Josefa (1867-1894)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QK6L-6KCH|title=Maryland, Baltimore Passenger Lists, 1820-1948|last=Melichar|first=|date=1883|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nShe married Vojtech Duban (from [[Mysl\u00edv|Mysliv]]) in [[Baltimore]]. She is the younger sister of Karolina who also married Vojtech after her passing.\n|\n|-\n|\n|c. 1883\n